The set `rootsOfUnity n Circle` is defined as `{z : Circle | z ^ n = 1}`.
We know that `rootsOfUnity n ℂ` (the set of `n`-th roots of unity in `ℂ`) is cyclic. This is because the map `k ↦ exp(2πik/n)` for `k ∈ {0, 1, ..., n-1}` is a generator of the cyclic group `rootsOfUnity n ℂ`.
The set `rootsOfUnity n Circle` is precisely the image of `rootsOfUnity n ℂ` under the map `z ↦ z` (i.e., the inclusion map), because `z ∈ rootsOfUnity n ℂ` if and only if `z ∈ rootsOfUnity n Circle` (as `rootsOfUnity n Circle` is defined as `{z : Circle | z ^ n = 1}`, which is exactly the condition for being an `n`-th root of unity in `ℂ`).

Since `rootsOfUnity n ℂ` is cyclic, and `rootsOfUnity n Circle` is a submonoid of `rootsOfUnity n ℂ` (because the map `z ↦ z` is a monoid homomorphism from `rootsOfUnity n Circle` to `rootsOfUnity n ℂ`, and `rootsOfUnity n Circle` is the preimage of `rootsOfUnity n ℂ` under this map), it follows that `rootsOfUnity n Circle` is also cyclic.

